    <text id="A2922T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>In this letter, Tyler &amp; Son encloses a receipt for goods purchased as
                    well as discussing the demands for various goods such as cattle, apples, cheese,
                    and soap.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="enclosure" id="d5">
                <p>Sales for Account of Mr Henry Ott<lb/>1865<lb/>June 26 1 Package Butter 84-15-69
                    @ 30 cents $20.70<lb/>Charges<lb/>Commission 5 <abbr expan="percent">pr
                    ct</abbr> $1.03<lb/><orig reg="Net">Nett</orig> proceeds to credit of 268
                    $19.67<lb/>Richmond 28<hi rend="super">th</hi> June 1865 Tyler &amp; Son</p>
            </div1>
            <div1 type="letter" id="d6">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Mr Henry Ott</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1865-06-28">28<hi rend="super">th</hi> June 1865</date>
                        <name type="place">Richmond</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>We enclose sales of Butter sent, and in the absence of any instructions how to
                    send the money we have left it subject to your order.</p>
                <p>While butter has somewhat declined <hi rend="underline">good</hi> is still in
                    demand, but the stock of common is so large that it is dull and slow sale.</p>
                <p>Dried Apples and Country Cheese are also dull at present. Country Soap if good
                    would sell, as also Vinegar, but a new or weak article of Vinegar would not.
                    Trade opens slowly owing to the scarcity of money.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Most <abbr expan="Respectfully">Resply</abbr></salute>
                    <signed>Tyler &amp; Son</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
